textDisplay:
Basically if one trains as a Powerlifter you wouln't get larger. Most competitive Powerlifters aren''t massive or looking like a bodybuilder. Most look like they don't workout. Even competitive Powerlifters. And of course they can be super strong.

Also think about diet. That matters a lot too if one isn't trying to get bigger. Its the other half of the equation.

Guys like Mike O'Hearn train for both. As a powerlifter and bodybuilder. I do the same. I'm stronger than Ive ever been e.g. when I was in my 20's...

Bruce Lee. (I used to be a huge fan of his since I was a boy). He's been "talked about" as being "ahead of his time" (in his time) as far as the type of training he did yett he did a lot of drugs later in his life. And was never a competitive martial artist. It was like he knew how to (IMHO) how to build enough muscle and have the flexiblity to do the kicks and mvoes he did on film. As if he were the JCVD of the early 70's. I think he was highly overrated. People I respect as athletes are or where champions. People who've ;paid their dues and were tested against elite athletes. Not just talkers. Or people who's goal is "to show".

Even JCVD competed back in Belgium....to some degree.

textDisplay:
1) Strength more about training the nervous system and the muscle just get trained because you can not train the nervous system much with out getting them involved some.

2) Getting bigger is about hypertrophy of the muscles so your mostly trying to train them physically and metabolically with as much volume at a moderate load as you can while still having good form.

3) (Load/Intensity=Strength but Volume=Permanente Physicals Adaptation) this is especialy true if load is moderate.

4) Most sports and average athletes but not all would benefit more from anaerobic endurance over aerobic endurance even though that point is still largely missed by most athletes and how best to train for it is also largely missed by most athletes.

5) If someone is lifting properly with heavy weights or doing challenging body weight work they do not need to separately and directly focus on core work their core will be almost entirely built and functional from daily training. Improperly technique, reliance on machines and lack of variety in bodyweight training is what creates weak non-functional core and glutes!

Anyone that thinks they need to do extensive and systematic core work fully programed into their workouts has been misled by some well meaning but misguided trainers or had coaches that where lacking some important information. The only time that is needed is to correct an athlete that has made it to a fairly advanced level with out developing those basic strengths and skills in an attempt to prevent them from getting hurt. So you are retraining them to do what they should have been doing all along to get them quickly to a point of safety. Same thing is true of posterior chain if the athlete has been properly trained and exercising properly than the posterior chain will be taken care of and fully functions it is improper training that creates posterior chain issues not some fundamental flaw in the human body!

textDisplay: Easy! Heavy weight low reps, isometrics, sprints, high rep kettlebell swings and snatches and toss in some Turkish get-ups. If you do bodyweight  keep total rep count low and focus on circuits with sprints and other body movement exercises and isometrics. Never train to the point of fatigue end each workout feeling fresh and energized. Do these things and it will be difficult to gain significant mass. You will be more fit than 90% of the Earths population and stronger. Any time you think you are getting too big back off the resistance exercise or body weight calisthenics and focus on isometrics and sprints for a month of two. If that is still too much race walk and do isometrics.

textDisplay:
I agree with you end statements whole heartedly. I think allot of people under estimate how hard it is to really blow up to a body builder standard. No one accidentally ends up looking like arnie in his Mr Olympia era. If any average size beginner woke up tomorrow with an extra 5kg of muscle spread out proportionately, they would be very happy :D .
I think that while there is a bad culture of size over function for some, there is also a bad counterculture around that dismisses mass gaining exercises as only for vain bullies. I used to be in the counterculture camp. Now I realise both are a bad approach to feeling, doing and looking good.

textDisplay:
Unfortunately Force (N) = mass (kg) × acceleration (m/s²). If you consider the variation between min/max fast twitch and response speeds of all modern athletes and min/max mass of the same athletes you would realize that the speed variable spectrum is way smaller compared to the mass variable. In other words there is more variation in weight than speed in athletes, especially regarding potential and ability to control the max result. Basically all athletes speed variables are more similar than their mass variables. What this means is if you want power relative to your fellow man then avoiding mass, the more easily increased factor with the highest max end, is..well, it's just stupid af.
All that said your list was very creative and basically true, tho It makes use of some semantics regarding the initial posed question

textDisplay: I feel like these exercises would also benefit people who are trying to get back in shape or are healing from an injury. Simple isometric pushing and pulling is great for muscles but as mentioned -it helps to build tendon strength. Tendon strength is essential for joint stability when you’re going through any number of exercises. If you’re heavier person or you have balance issues do to age or injury, than this joint stability becomes even more important. It can be has hard or as gentle as you need it to be for wherever you’re starting out.

textDisplay: I used to call it going "mighty mouse" aka tiny but mighty. textDisplay: I'm always surprised at how heavy a 45 lb container of water is vs a 45 lb dumbbell, but I figured out that it's because the center of gravity is lower and I'm usually carrying water with 1 hand vs usually carrying 2 dumbbells at the same time.  1 hand carrying involves different spinal muscles that are not trained with lifting dumbbells.  Functional lifting is very different from gym training and should be incorporated.  Someone can lift a 300 lb barbell in a deadlift but picking up a 300 lb box off the floor would be impossible for the same person if they don't train for it.
textOriginal: I'm always surprised at how heavy a 45 lb container of water is vs a 45 lb dumbbell, but I figured out that it's because the center of gravity is lower and I'm usually carrying water with 1 hand vs usually carrying 2 dumbbells at the same time.  1 hand carrying involves different spinal muscles that are not trained with lifting dumbbells.  Functional lifting is very different from gym training and should be incorporated.  Someone can lift a 300 lb barbell in a deadlift but picking up a 300 lb box off the floor would be impossible for the same person if they don't train for it.

textDisplay:
This might be bro science or maybe even just complete bullshit from yours truly. But as an athlete who has played 3 sports all my life I have noticed that whenever I am doing lots and lots of cardio ( both distance and speed ) that my weight and bodyfat goes down but my strength tends to incerase still but slowly. For example I am down from 225 pounds to now about 185 roughly every day highest end of day weight. however my deadlift has shot up from 315-405 pounds over 3 months and my overhead press, dumbell chest press and squat has also skyrocketed. However it is also worth nothing a few things.

1. I am 17 years old as of the end of september so my strength may be due to other reasons.

2. I have deadlifting more frequently as well as running sooooooo much more frequently as well as walking ex. 2 miles to school plus 1 h 30 mn in gym as well as 2.5-3 mile run at rougly 8-9 minute pace

textDisplay: How to get strong without getting big? Easy, be in the 85 percent of males genetically pre-disposed to minimal to moderate hypertrophy in response to strength training, and refrain from taking gear. You will certainly then get stronger without getting substantially bigger. And if you're in that much smaller percentage of hyper-responders, you'll get bigger regardless of your training protocol unless you're depriving yourself of key nutrients or driving yourself to death with heavy cardio.

textDisplay: Minimize muscle damage during training & minimize metabolic overload if you want to stay small as you gain strength.  Stop at 70-90% fatigue to avoid lactic acid buildup.  Acid will lead to vascularity rather than power, as your body prioritizes detox. Lower reps at higher weights with longer rest intervals.  And make sure all your lifts are compound, involving the entire body.  Most importantly is doing a lot of body weight training.  When you have to lift yourself a lot, your body will opt for strength instead of mass.  Calisthenics with added weights as you progress.  Target your tendons by exercising throughout the day for small bursts instead of doing it all at once.

1.)Don't eat crap (no gluten, gmo corn, fried food, soy, oils(use only butter/lard), don't overcook meat(only eat medium rare), no nitrates, carbonated drinks, skin of baked potatoes, sugar, milk)

6.) cardio

textDisplay:
Strong is quite an ambiguous word to some. If you want to be strong (literally) lifting weight x times your body weight then you need to train your myofibrillar muscle by getting used to heavy load -> low reps training. Getting that mind muscle connection to recruit more muscle in the movement.

If you want to be strong (Kickass) then learn a form of self defense. Lifting heavy weight is a skill. Same with punching, kicking and grappling.

Either way if you have discipline and have a good diet. That side effect of your training will show thus better looking body.
Side note though lifting heavy weight has a threshold. You won't really be able to lift outward that threshold without gaining more weight (fat or muscle). Cause this 2 help support your bones when under load.

Rather than making the muscle fibers you've got, bigger or swell, why not train so that your muscle fibers multiply? textDisplay: As a martial artist, I try to increase speed and strength together with staying flexible. I don't just train for competitions with rules though, getting mugged, street fights, bar fights, etc., these are things that can happen at any time no matter how careful you are. While being bigger and having more muscle adds intimidation and makes people think twice about messing with you, there's no guarantee someone stronger or tougher or armed won't try something. That's why I would rather have more strength, speed and endurance if I come across those situations, because size isn't always going to work, but overall physical ability won't let you down. Thanks for the great video!

textDisplay: Talk of dad strength makes me think about mum strength. All that extra time carrying a baby which grows into a wiggling toddler - especially if they don't tolerate a pram but love being carried like my child did. textDisplay: This is basically the workout I've been doing for the last year and a half (I didn't workout for nine years before that and I didn't workout for one year during the pandemic), influenced by Bruce Lee to increase my SMV (sexual market value). Absorb what is useful and apply, then create your own. My new workout is mostly stretching, using very light weights all stretched out throughout the day. I stay away from glutes and traps because I don't want that bubble butt and "incredible hulk" look. With mom's sexy legs and dad's handsomeness, the results have been amazing. I do Isometrics and a few of Bruce's exercises, dancing in place to music, so intense it burns after 30 seconds, and a couple dozen of my own exercises. I'll be adding more kicking and punching to further sculpt myself. I target those weak muscles you talk about, pushing walls, the side of my desk and squating and pulling the edge of my bar. What a wonderful life

textDisplay: I wrestled all they way up to the international level and have trained with and been coached by Olympians. The sport of wrestling is loaded with guys who have "freak" strength without bulk. Until you have seen or competed against it, it's hard to fathom how powerful some of those higher level athletes are in the sport. But much of the training and strength development in wrestling is "isolation" and "core" based. Imagine spending your entire workout with someone your own weight resisting every movement you make. Bruce Lee had an appreciation for wrestling for reason. I would recommend any young man/woman wanting to intensify their strength without the bulk effect to get involved in a grappling style training or even join one of the grappling arts.
textOriginal: I wrestled all they way up to the international level and have trained with and been coached by Olympians. The sport of wrestling is loaded with guys who have "freak" strength without bulk. Until you have seen or competed against it, it's hard to fathom how powerful some of those higher level athletes are in the sport. But much of the training and strength development in wrestling is "isolation" and "core" based. Imagine spending your entire workout with someone your own weight resisting every movement you make. Bruce Lee had an appreciation for wrestling for reason. I would recommend any young man/woman wanting to intensify their strength without the bulk effect to get involved in a grappling style training or even join one of the grappling arts.

textDisplay: Coming from a combat sports background, the desire to get big without a functional base was always foreign to me. To me, getting bigger means having to move up a weight class and fighting guys who would not only be the same weight, but also taller, longer and have less aerobic demands on their bodies. Getting strong, more explosive and having more endurance for your natural weight class has always made more sense to me haha. So I'm grateful channels like yours exist for this reason

textDisplay:
I'm obviously not as knowledgable as you about fitness but i can't help but feel that Calisthenics could/should have been mentioned. You generally get more lean than bulky doing bodyweight training like calisthenics and the statics and positions you get into build up your smaller muscle that things like weight training can't do making you more stronger relatively. Calisthenics also builds tendon strength like you mentioned when doing the more advanced moves.

As someone who has been doing calisthenics for about 6 months i've only gained about 1-2kg of muscle. I appear a lot more bigger than i used to but my weight hasn't changed much at all. I would say my strength would be close to doubled for certain movements along with my grip strength being far stronger. Calisthenics is also one of the ways to achieve superhuman strength and it would be interesting to know if Bruce Lee did things like the planche, handstand push ups, front lever and back lever... He did basically inven the Dragon Flag which i would say is a calisthenics move since it's difficult to add weight to that or do in the gym

textDisplay:
I would probably say I am Interested in a combo of strength and size. I don't care about aesthetic, it's just a case that I already have that strongman physique so I understand the benefits of having a layer of thick muscle and fat. Hell I'm getting into sumo at this point, I'm just a bulky fighter.

I've legit been in the heavyweights since I started middle school. I was 200lbs when I was 10 and that was with my wrestling coach working my ass into the ground. I just have always been a big motherfucker.

I appreciate the quality of lean muscle though. Some of the scariest people I've ever fought were tiny dudes that could hit like a truck and were impossible to catch.

Now funny thing is that my favorite thing to train by far is grip strength. I love using the captains of crush grip strengtheners religiously. I also condition my knuckles every couple days by punching some wooden boards.

textDisplay: I think most people who are behind this goal don't realize they won't get that big anyway, so I don't know if this mindset is beneficial since there are some benefits inherent to muscle mass itself, like increased metabolism and insulin sensitivity, joint protection among other things. If you are not on steroids and not bulking to look huge, you won't get even close, you may even get pissed off thinking you would like to look a little bit more jacked lol. This is a very interesting video however, and very usefull for athletes and specially powerlifters who want to squeeze a little more strength without having to move a weightclass, maybe isometrics and negatives can be done during peaking for a meet? It makes sense to me since the negatives can literally allow you to handle weights well beyond your training max which might result in a slightly bigger neurological response to this last phase of training.

textDisplay:
I grew up on the country side where we did a lot of manual labor, none of the men there looked particulary big or ripped, but all of them have more strength than event he bigger guys I've seen in the gym, I used to see this skinny woodcutter guys literally dragging huge tree logs that I could not even flinch even in my 20's, based on the parts that they cut them into I'd assume most of the logs they work with weight over 50 kilograms, maybe even 100 kilograms and they do the labor for hours a day. I guess you are a lot stronger than you'd think.

I have better defined musculature and am also lower body fat than my dad, I can do more push ups and pull ups than him because I'm used to doing them, but he can do other things he's used to better than me such as digging holes to plant trees or chopping wood that I find too hard to get through, while he's almost 50

P.S you also use your legs on the spade after you stick it in the ground, digging holes works pretty much all the body but your core is probably hit the most, using a spade overall requires great core management

textDisplay: When I was in sophomore of high school I took a weights class where in addition to lifting, the teacher gave us lectures on different types of lifting so that we would be able to develop our own workout plan and continue outside of class. I walked in at 115lbs and had never lifted any weights in my life. I could barely balance the 45lb bar, and by the end of the school year I was 125lbs and had a bench max of 200lbs. That's more than triple my starting strength and a gain of only 10lbs, following a strength training plan of 2-8 reps at 85-100% of one rep max for 4-6 sets per exercise, with 2 exercises per muscle group.

textDisplay: Farmer strength is just a easy way to say "repetitious hard work" strength. Im a lumber mill worker an im only 150 lb. Fact is i can out press and bench most of my 180-200 lb friends. I had to explain to them my job is a 10 hour work out in 120°f heat. So the work outs they view as hard. Dont even register to me. Ontop of that ive noticed my cardio is miles ahead of them just naturally. When your breathing in 120°f heat for 10 hours strate at a blistering pace you build an unnatural level of stamina. Ontop of your threshold for discomfort is much higher allowing you to push through workout pain and inturn allowing you to work out longer. Most of the time i stop doing rep's not because im tired. But because i dont want to injure something minor, that turns into something major do to my regular job requirements.

It made total sense that a complete transformation into a stronger form of super saiyan would be a form that made you hulking mass of muscle, no the next level should be obviously a more condense and compact form that focus all that energy to make an even more stronger power in an optimal way.

textDisplay: The way I got stronger and more powerful without getting bigger was getting a job in the moving industry. every day except weekends, for 8-13 hrs a day, I lift heavy things, move quickly with them, climbing up and down stair and carrying them to and from areas that are anywhere from 50-300 meters apart. It is a large variety of deadlifts, squats, farmers carry, team carry, max load with low reps, medium load with very high reps, and working until failure and then continuing to work (just because your tired does not mean the job is done) weights vary from 50lbs to over 800lbs (team lifting obviously, im not eddie hall XD) but I regularly lift and carry more than double my body weight (im about 140lbs lifting up to 300lbs)

textDisplay: On "Farmer's Power' That is true. My great-grandfather worked all his life, when he was 6 he was going with the ox (s) and pushing this long manual plow, then when he was 16 he was breaking rocks with a  hammer and finally after the second world war he became a fisherman-pulling his own boat by himself (long wooden boat that was made for 15 people/fishermen) by that time he was 89 years old. People were looking at him holding the boat with his right hand (his left hand had a crutch because his legs were shot by a Gatling gun during the war) ...so like I said with one hand he was pulling the boat at 89 all the way into the water by himself and then he was putting it back on the beach after he caught some fish. This man helped us all, his strength was unbelievable....was he muscular? Nope, he just had power....I never could win in an arm-wrestling match with him....not even when he was 97 years old.

textDisplay: This young man's approach to "health" has been mine for over 20 years. The only difference is that I use less weights. Nevertheless his application of principles of exercise most cannot grasp even with his good explanations, and in my opinion, the reason why, is people are "followers" rather than leaders. Leaders succumb to the effectiveness of what works for the "long haul" of with have you. Things that keep us striving for the best within ourselves that is continuously effective through the duration of our lives. I'm 53 years old, and I've ALWAYS utilized the same principles of exercising for many, many years. I'm fitter, stronger, healthier than most young and anyone my age. I'm into quality of life, not quantity. Over 73% of the U.S. population is unhealthy and overweight. I refuse to succumb to the "follower" attitude that most have, keeping them on the path to a quick death. Our mental, physical, spiritual health is absolutely important, in any day and age, and here in 2021, it is even moreso. The weakness I witness of people is staggering. Weakness in mind and body. There are NO EXCUSES regardless of how difficult you THINK your life is.

textDisplay: My dad was a lumberjack from Quebec. A Canuck. He sold firewood on the side, which we delivered to the clients. From the time I was 12 or so until I joined the Army, I split two cords of wood by hand every evening after school, and at least 10 each day on Saturday and Sunday (luckily, during summer vacation he left the tree tops in the forest, so I could go fishing and hunting!).  The weekend was the time we delivered all that wood (I had two younger brothers to help with the loading and stacking, but I did all the splitting).  At 5'10" and a 145 lbs I was unbeatable at arm wrestling by any of the muscly gym jocks in my High School.  Ah, nostalgia (this was 40 years ago)!  Thanks for triggering the memories!

Im 60kg and would stack 70 kg wooden pallets 10 high, it came from holding parts above my head in awkward positions and carrying fuel for the machines as a 10 year old. by the time i was 13 i could carry two 20L up a rocky unstable mining road for hundreds of meters, one thing i think helped was the variety, as we lived in the bush and done everything ourselves. as the down time of going to town would cost us time we could be mining.
When i moved to town and started working on farms at 16, i always excelled to higher positions as the useful kid that got stuff done fast. I think my best effort was cutting turf, in one day i cut and stacked 2700 square meters of grass and then laid 500 square meters of lawns in 14 hrs and I pulled 84 hrs that week and wasn't hurt by it.
Now i've been a single dad for 10 years still weigh 60 kg and still can work dam hard. but gaining weight is near impossible, but i don't mind being lean.

textDisplay:
As I was taught in high school biology back in 1989, you can only develop two pounds, (one kilo), of functional muscle mass per year. When I was younger I was dense and could lift much more than I looked like I could. I did not have access to weights so I worked out against my own body mass, I also took advice from Jack Lalanne and stretched every muscle group I planned to work out that night both before and after my routine.

That's the secret, low weight/high rep, controlled muscle movements through the entire range of motion, lots of stretches, and years of patience to develop true, functional, muscle density.

The inverse builds bulk.

High weight low rep focused in the area of motion of the muscle you want to fill out builds bulk but that bulk is not as strong as above.

This is how you cheat the system, use bulk training to fill out to where you want to be by "push to fail" routines with max weight that leave you barely able to finish a set of three, eight reps each. When you get close to what you want swap over to high rep/ low weight like sets of five with sixteen reps each, if you finish that five and can do a six set completely up your resistance. If you finish and you can only do half of a sixth set, you're in the right range of resistance. If you finish and can do less than half of a sixth set you should drop your weight the next time you work that muscle group. Stretch your intended muscle groups both before and after the routine to improve recovery and healing.

textDisplay:
I've been farming most of my life...farmer strength is a thing! It's not just the small activities. Sure, we dig a hole for a post...but that's not the only post hole we dig, we have several miles needing a post every 16 feet...and it needed to be done yesterday. So, there we are at the end of a hard day, worn out and tired, with all our post holes dug and posts set....knowing tomorrow we get up bright and early to get all the animals fed, and other chores completed, before we can go back with a post driver and put the steel posts in between the posts we put in yesterday....all the while knowing we have several miles of wire to hang and stretch the next day, and cows that needed moving ages ago LOL
It's not just the small activities...it's the daily routine, and the extra work done on top, and doing what needs to be done no matter how worn out or tired you are....so, we aren't just mysteriously strong, we're stubborn!

textDisplay: Isn't it odd how people who do calisthenics and gymnastics don't necessarily have big muscles but they can put their bodies in positions and activities that the big, puffy muscled bodybuilders can't do.  There are a lot of gaps in just weightlifting.  You find that out when you try calisthenics and gymnastics.  Or, even yoga.  Try some of those yoga poses.  See if you can hold your leg up at the proper height for as long as necessary.  LET ME ADD - don't overdo the isometrics at first with too much straining and too many sets.  Straining your tendons and ligaments takes a lot longer to heal than recovering from muscle soreness.  Speaking from experience.  Tendon and ligament pain HURTS.

textDisplay:
Literally just about three days ago I was talking to a friend who never trained anything, was never athletic at all (& still isn't) about starting going to the gym. While we were talking I gave him some introduction on what to expect, explained some basic exercises he could do, how to do them, what supplements to take, how and when to take or if he even should take them etc. At the end of it all he says: "Man, I don't want to go to the gym, develop big muscles and get too big". Of course I didn't say anything to his face, since it's important to be encouraging to someone who never tried something, but in my mind I was thinking "What a load of fucking bullshit, what are you on about?". If you NEVER lifted weights in your life, you're not gonna on your first month, start benching crazy weights and screaming "Lightweight, baby!". Second thing I thought to myself is "Why wouldn't you want to develop muscles?". He's already, well, a big guy, so turning fat into muscles would be a great thing. He would get to keep his figure, but transform it into something better - a good looking muscular body that he also feels good and healthy in.
Some people really amaze.

He would do things like casually do a one arm pullup, or pick something up that two guys could barely budge. The crazy thing is I rarely saw him at the gym, he rarely worked out. The two or three times I saw him, he was lifting more than some of the massive meat monsters. I vividly remember he went to this cable machine adjusted for biceps and put the weight all the way down at 290 and did 10 reps like it was nothing. Mind you I can barely do 1 rep. He leaves for about a minute to bullshit, then comes back and does another 10 reps without breaking a sweat.

textDisplay:
Prior to working at a hardware store, I was a couch potato.
Doing some lifting , moving cement bags and steel bars around the warehouse and loading them on trucks. My body was always sore everyday for a couple of months. Id go home and slept like a baby immediately from exhaustion. A year later, my gf at the time noticed that I was squeezing her hands tighter when we were holding hands, when I myself wasnt aware and I just assumed I was holding her hand the way I used to. That was the time I noticed I had better forearm and grip strength and better mind-muscle connection.

textDisplay:
Better to be big IMHO (with a combo of muscle and fat)
1. More intimidating - best method of self-defence is being too big to be messed with in the first place
2. Padding - muscle and fat both provide excellent protection from physical trauma (obese ppl are more likely to survive car crashes)
3. Once you get big enough martial artists will have a much harder time applying grappling/throw techniques to you (obviously you're not immune, but anyone who has rolled with a much bigger guy in BJJ will confirm this - and yes this applies to martial arts where you "use your opponent's weight against them")
4. Striking arts also less effective at delivering KOs if you have a strong neck (again, you can still get KO'd - the effect is less pronounced than with grappling)
5. In a survival situation you will last a lot longer because you will be better insulated from the cold and be able to burn fat for calories (shredded ppl will start breaking down their muscles within days)

I am 55 and stand at 6ft 2in in bare feet. So hopefully I can hit my goal and continue my path to keeping lean and getting strong without building to much muscle.

textDisplay: Working in a timber merchant for 10 years, I started as a weakling and when I left I was a lazy colossus.  It was sometimes a day of scratching my balls for eternity and others it was about 6-7 hours of hateful toil.  Massive railway sleepers, beastly joists, or hundreds of smaller lengths would pass as one.  I would look at people paying to lift weight as if they were mad.  Cycling to work would turbo-charge the effects.  Far too old to even attempt a similar output nowadays - enjoy your youth whilst it lasts!

textDisplay:
Completely agree with farmer strength. I’ve worked as a granite fabricator for 6years, lifting machinery all day, lifting granite, buckets, tool boxes, ect. Everything’s relatively heavy in the shop so you’re always having to use force of some sort for long periods of time. Remedy this with kettlebells, & resistance bands and and you have grip strength like no other

I recently started BJJ and this has helped me a lot in training. So far I’ve been able to out grip my rolling partners, I can hold a grip long enough to burn them out so I can make a move. I’m a short 5’5 guy, slight lean built with some quarantine weight I gained lol. All my partners are 5’10” +.

textDisplay: There is one important variable you missed. To get big, especially considerably big, you need to be in a caloric surplus (eating daily a bit more than you burned off), theoretically if you eat at your maintenance level or slightly below it, you probably won’t be putting on much size. I have never been to a gym in my life, never needed to. My sister and her husband goes to the gym 2 times a week, constantly talking about deadlift PR's and the sort. They look a great deal more "fit" than me and ofcourse act like it.

But when it came time for her to move to a new house it took both my sister and her husband to lift one side of a cedar dresser, while i can easily lift the other with just one arm. I would show off similar things as well, like the tractor tire she has in her backyard that she flips for 20 minutes a day. Despite never lifting a tractor tire i can also flip the tire with 1 arm.

Core strength is very important for overall performance, never neglect the core muscles.

textDisplay:
If you want to be strong in a physical activity:

Practice your technique religiously. The human body in brute strength alone has limits. You’re not going to clean n jerk 400lbs with strength alone. You won’t be a good martial artist in strength/physical training alone.

Your body will adapt to whatever your training is. The body achieves what the mind wants, or breaks trying. Don’t focus on big, small, lean, etc. Focus on function and the rest will follow.

Getting bigger is something you have to deliberately do, and it has it’s place. If you’re a runner, you will end up with a runners body. If you’re a strongman competitor, you will end up with that body.

Getting bigger is something you have to deliberately do, and it has it’s place. If you’re a runner, you will end up with a runners body. If you’re a strongman competitor, you will end up with that body.

textDisplay: The real reason.... Type 1 muscle consumes oxygen and glycogen provided by bloodstream. Type 2 muscle consumes ATP located in the muscle, so some of the size is the fuel itself not muscle. Type 2A or type 2x muscle is type 2 muscle that was converted to use the bloodstream for fuel. You will get smaller you won’t lift as much, but power over time is highest of all. This is the reason most athletes may appear to have average builds, when in reality they are physical elites.

textDisplay: Isometrics are definitely where it's at. You get really strong in a really short amount of time, and it takes literally seconds to do. Crazy stuff

textDisplay:
When I was younger, I did HVAC rough-ins, and just generally pushed my 5'10" 140lbs frame as hard as I could on a daily basis. I always tried my damnedest to keep up with the bigger guys, like my cousin who was my height but at 180lbs of solid muscle. A guy who broke weight lifting records at his highschool at the age of 15, benchpressing 410lbs. But I managed to keep up with him in the manual labor work that we did. If he lifted the 200lbs bundle of duct pipe to carry it from the truck to the house, I lifted the 200lbs bundle of duct pipe and carried it across the job site on my shoulder. I never really got any bigger, but I got whole hell of a lot stronger. I was wiry and sinewy, and came to realize later, ridiculously strong for my size, with loads of endurance and explosive power. I could do well over 100 pushups or chin-ups after only a few days of attempting it, then I started doing these with a weighted vest, adding 30lbs to my body, and still pushing myself to well over 100 of each. I never could get any bigger, but I was explosively powerful in my ability to lift and move heavy objects, including my own body.

Now, in my late 30's, I'm finally able to bulk up and build muscle mass, but I'm not quite as powerful as I used to be, despite having 25lbs more muscle on my frame. And I think it's because I no longer do manual labor.

textDisplay:
The biggest secret to "Farmer's Strength" is they perform the same movements the same exact way frequently.

This allows the muscles to adapt to the movements (i.e., exercises) therefore becoming more efficient at doing said movements. As your body becomes more efficient the muscle fibers do not break down as much and as a result less and less muscle growth.

However, you still can build on the various attributes: endurance, strength and speed/power. And as a bonus, you do not get as sore.

*this is usual the point where body builders and mass gainers change up their routine to maintain peak and optimal fiber breakdown for maximum hypertrophy.

Simply do not do this and continue the same routine with the same exercises using the same movements. Then you can build on the targeted attribute.

In addition: you can try to tap into "Hysterical Strength" by mentally inducing an incident where a loved one's life is in danger and you need to perform said movement with heavy weights in order to save them. You have to emotionally invested for it to work.

As Bruce Lee said, "You need emotional content."

textDisplay:
I work in a chemical plant. Depending on the building I'd work in, there would be days of slinging 50+ pound bags of powder, moving 500+ pound drums or carrying 35 pound containers (one in each hand) back and forth for hours out of the day.

In addition, we own wooded land in the mountains. One of our projects consisted of lifting large (100-150lb) stones into a wheelbarrow and moving them to the other end of the property (~300 yards) through the woods, then moving them into place to create a dock 🤣

You get pretty strong doing stuff like that...

textDisplay:
One thing Ive noticed with my dad (who is a farmer) is that he has such endurance. I guess its also a sort of determination that goes along with it. Its like hes willing himself to hold that thing or pull/push on the object etc. Even though hes almost 71 years old hes one the stronger persons I know, but at the same time hes quite thin, weighing only around 75 kg.
Its an odd thing. There have been many times when Ive been surprised at how strong he is.
Most of the time hes by himself and thus forced to do it him self. Changing gearbox on a tractor, hangin 4x6m garage doors, holding a chunk of iron whilst welding it to something and so on. Like with the gearbox thing. Once I was helping him and found it almost impossible for the two of us, but then you realize hes done it by himself once before!?

One time he asked my sisters man for help with something heavy. My sisters man has trained regularly in the gym for 25 years (since he was 17) and can move some considerable weights in the gym. But my dad was very dissapointed indeed.

textDisplay:
hey man! been watching a bunch of your videos for a while and really interesting stuff. I am personally particularly interested in connective tissue training, especially progressions. For example, if a person is injured, what would be the most ideal place to start? I understand that would be eccentric training. I also think isometrics and plyometrics are essentially progressions to eccentric training as far as connective tissue conditioning is concerned, awesome if you are healthy and supple, but less than ideal if your connective tissues are injured/not ready. I know Coach Chris Sommers states that connective tissue takes about 210 fays to fully adapt, but I don't think he outlines any particular training principles for people that are not elite/Olympic level athletes.

Would love to hear your thoughts!

textDisplay:
One dimension of strength often overlooked is also nervous system strength. Your muscle output capacity is limited by your tendons but your overall capacity is determined by how constant/intensely your nerves can continue firing. That will pull out a seemingly unlimited amout of strength which is never utilised.

Building the size and network of nerves is a slow process and would further explain that farmer strength. But also has an element of will power (intention) that causes the nerve to fire in the first place.

textDisplay:
Real strength comes from recruiting multiple muscle groups (as many as possible) to get the job done.
Most gym training is focused on training certain muscle groups in isolation. This causes your neuro-muscular connections to get used to recruiting one muscle group at a time.
If you train to use everything at once, you'll be able to recruit everything at once when needed.

textDisplay:
Just my story proving its possible. Never used weights but breakdance for 6yrs. Look at pro breakdancers. They are just big enough but not body builders. Some look as if they never gained any muscles. I did various pushups and sit ups with cardio but only up to the point where breakdancing was enough of a workout (did not workout hard anymore, or much at all after 2 years). Used to be able to walk back and forth across a room multiple times on my hands, balance my head, shoulder, and forearm as a trianle on the ground and lift into a one hand handstand all just from kicking my legs toward the ceiling and using my neck muscles and abs to lift then lastly my arm to push up.

As a teen i never worked out for looks. I never heard of "sets" until i got into college. Just gunned it til it hurt. It was always performance first, so i worked out as if i was performing how i imagined myself breakdancing. Just burning and paining. But getting older i can see how this isnt safe 😂

textDisplay: Commercial fishing developed my grip and core.  Chopping frozen bait, baiting thousands of hooks, snapping them onto miles of moving line while the boat is rising, falling, pitching and rolling is quite the set of chores.  Then of course we had to haul it back in, unclip it all, head and gut and stow the catch, make another set and...  I gained very fit strength and size without even suspecting it under all that polypropylene, wool, and raingear.  When the weather was too dangerous to fish we kayaked that cold surf for fun.  We ate lots of fish, potatoes, and cabbage.  Dang that life could swing  from fun to horrific in a heartbeat but it kept you strong.

textDisplay:
I do mostly body weight workouts. chin-ups, dips, squats and modified push ups. (I like the idea of training to better move my body through space.) and always in one minute interval training.

To get stronger, I started by using a ten lb weighted back pack for all of my body weight workouts. Then I spent a month "dirty bulking" to add about ten extra pounds (putting on weight by eating more and increasing my workouts). After that month I spent the next two months eating right, doing more cardio and decreasing the number of body weight training days a bit. HOWEVER, whenever I lost a pound of body weight, I would add a pound to my back pack. That way, even though I was losing weight, my body was still able to lift and move the same weight.

The interval training pushed me harder than doing a set number because working against a clock makes you work harder to get more reps in the same amount of time. And increasing the pack weight as I lost body fat was easier because my body was still lifting the same amounts even as I was losing fat.

Best part, when it comes to body movement, I am faster and more agile because my muscles are trained to move a 20 pound heavier version of me.

textDisplay: So true this man speaks facts like there are soo many "fitness gurus" that I've watched that tell you that you shouldn't train your one rep max and that you wont get stronger if you do but this really confused me because a few weeks ago during quarantine my one rep max was 80kg for flat bench press and i have a body weight of 60kg, but then i started training my one rep max by implementing Greasing the Groove  basically i just did one rep of 80kg every hour on the hour 10 times in that day and i got stronger. The next day i was able to do 2 reps every hour on the hour and  then the next day 6 reps.  After just 1 week of training like this my new one rep max became 95kg.  I was shocked because for a long time i was stuck at 80kg and i always thought that the reason i wasn't getting stronger was because my diet wasn't on point, i wasn't eating enough, but that wasn't the case. My problem was that I never saw training as practice and I feel like a lot of people don't see training as practice as well and that's why a lot of people struggle to get stronger and they plateau and then they come up with this misconception that the only way to get stronger from here is to get bigger but that's really not the case. I won't lie being bigger definitely does give you an edge but it does not mean that in order to reach a certain level of strength you have to be a certain size. The fact of the matter is the more you practice something the better at it you'll get at it and that includes weight lifting as well and ALL areas of fitness.  You're bench press you're pull ups say for example you can only do one rep of a pull up if you keep practicing that one rep over and over again it will eventually turn into 2 reps then 3 reps and more reps.

textDisplay: I went from snowboarding and skateboarding daily to breaking my hand and working as a pharmacy tech answering phones and counting pills for 8yrs eating garbage and developing a gluten allergy that went undiagnosed maybe my whole life, I had asthma and developed a nasty skin condition. Is it just like mental restriction or something physiological happening to reduce the strength?

textDisplay: Recently I started training with sandbags. I've been lifting for a bunch of years now, mainly focusing on big compound movements, bodyweight exercises and kettlebell training. Also I've been practicing BJJ for over a year now, so after that I was quite shocked how sandbags kicked my a@@, the unpredictabily and awkwardness in those exercises really help a lot building strength I feel. My lower back and glutes end up being more fried than after say a maximum effort deadlift workout, I guess because I'm forced to work in more disadvantegous patterns and thus generate more torque in angels I'm not used to. That's pretty much how farmer strength is built over a long period of time I guess.

textDisplay:
Bruce lee hardened his "weapons" like his fists and feet in order to counteract the friction in the opposing force completely so that he would have to use a lesser overall force in order to achieve a positive result.
For an example:

Heavyweights: force needed to achieve a positive blow of force while counteracting the opposing force's friction is "2"
The opposing force is "-1" which means
Total result in force is a positive "1"

Bruce lee: with his hardened fists that negate the opposing force's friction means that in order to achieve a positive blow of force he would need only "1"
The opposing force is "0" since it has been negated which means
Total result in force is a positive "1"

Same result as the heavyweight

If you have cinder blocks for your fists wouldn't they do more impact in force then you would barehanded? The reason is that unlike your hands, they aren't soft so if they go against a soft target then the target wont be able to cause friction to oppose it on it's own.

Kinda like punching through water where you can punch right through it because there isn't an opposing force that causes friction.
So because of this bruce lee could focus more on his agility so that he can focus on carrying the "cinderblocks" a.k.a. his fists in order to reach his opponent faster so that he can overwhelm then with a volley of critical blows in order to win the fight. With fists as hard as that you can punch some solid things as if you were punching through water. Which allows you to keep the quick "flowing" speed without loosing the ability to "crash".
You become like water.

textDisplay:
Not that difficult if you understand the neuromuscular system at all. Strength isn't a product of muscle mass so much as it neurological adaptation. The body gets better at coordinating the firing of sarcomeres and engaging more myofibrils for a given action (which is why variety and complex motions are important to work into your program). The best method? High resistance, in the neighborhood of a 5RM, if not a bit more.

Hypertrophy does more for sustained moderate resistance due to increased sarcoplasmic glygogen stores and a larger number of myfibril heads that can sustain contraction for a longer period of time. It does not lead to substantial gains in strength, however, or at least not compared to neurological adaptation.

textDisplay:
From personal experience:
Training with super high reps and not moving onto a higher weight until a certain rep number is achieved in one go, for example, benching 20 reps of a weight before increasing the weight by 10kg and moving on. Meanwhile eating in a deficit to maintain body mass and not increase it. That way your body has to forcefully adapt and get stronger without getting bigger.

All I can say is that I have done this personally and has worked for me. I believe not eating enough calories doesn't allow muscular growth but instead forces muscular density to increase. The result: super strong for your size. Btw don't know the scientific lirerature behind this.

textDisplay: Hauling hay, cutting/splitting/stacking firewood, driving fence posts, carrying 50lb bags of feed, hammering nails, walking heavy loads in a wheelbarrow....yep. Hammering nails and splitting firewood also dialed in my hand eye coordination along with being able to produce and transfer power to a single point. I see people hitting tires with a sledge hammer. That's good but training is much more effective if you are aiming and contacting a point the size of a small coin....like driving a steel stake in the ground, pulling it up and driving it over and over. Or splitting firewood where your aiming the blade at a crack in the log. That builds power and precision power transfer. Great for boxers.

textDisplay:
The secret is doing multijoint exercises.

Most gym equipment is designed for isolating only one main muscle group, which means by doing them you increase their size, but you don't really connect muscle groups with each other. That's why for functional strength it is best to do exercises which engage whole body at once (pull ups, push ups, deadlifts, squats, hanging leg raises to the bar - basically most bodyweight exercises).

The secret is doing *multijoint* exercises.

textDisplay:
Obviously the fitness industry, a billions of dollars a year industry, is designed to keep people misdirected, confused, and uneducated so they can easily sell you on their products. So it has lead people to think size is strength. Where there is a relationship between the ability to move or lift more weight or mass when the lifter has more mass, true strength is the relationship between the mass of the lifter and the mass of the load as well as the force the lifter can apply and the duration of work the lifter is capable of (force = mass * acceleration, work = force * distance)
All that being said true strength training is more about neurological programming and adaptation then physiological growth or hypertrophy. So for one to get stronger they must program training stimulus for the nervous system I.E. working sets of 1 - 3 using a weight range of 85% to above 100% of you 1 rep maximum effort.
But by all means muscle size is not the causation of strength. I’m glad to see people who understand that and appreciate a more pure form to their own fitness. 👍🏻

textDisplay: Work on tendon strength which I find improves a lot more during the negative of an exercise or long bouts of cardio. Tendons require no oxygen to operate and are much stronger than muscles are. The reason many junkies on Gear will have tendon issues is because tendons take a lot longer to strengthen and grow compared to muscles. The Gear will improve muscle size, user keeps lifting heavy weights, and because the tendons aren't caught up they get tendonitis, muscle tears, spine problem etc. This is where the term 'Grandpa strength' comes in, build up those tendons lads, eat all the ligaments in your chicken thighs and enjoy some broth!

textDisplay: While a lot of this is true, people get the wrong idea. When you do power exercises like plyometrics, you increase efficiency, yes. But these methods can't increase your absolute power. This is why you don't see strongmen focusing on plyometrics. It's the exact same reason you have weight classes in combat sports. It's a lot easier to generate more strength by increasing your muscle mass than it is to squeeze out a few more drops of performance out of a slimmer frame. It's like comparing a diesel-powered tank, to a finely tuned racing motorcycle.

I also didn’t notice the increased hypertrophy until people started to point it out

textDisplay:
I think this video's message is a huge pile of bullshit with a smelly smoke of truth on top.
How about some facts:
1. Bulkiness has a genetic limit & any genetic other limits can only be broken through substances. Period.
2. There is no difference between longer exercise durations or tensions or heavier weights to gain fit and healthy body, they all contribute to it, you would only be able to see a difference in your training style if you have reached an athletes fitness level in which your body is only reacting to a very strong intensity.
3. Humans are made differnently and depending on your genetic predispsitions, you have your very own advantages and disadvantages. So fuck comparing yourself to others. Longer arms will mean much harder pull-ups, but you may have also longer legs and sprint faster, and lift more, weight more. But you may take much longer to gain enough muscles on your big body to look fit compared to shorter humans, that will have a much easier time to gain enough muscles to look fit. But you know what?
4. It doesnt matter what you do for as long as you work on your very own inbalances properly that create that sore back or that deliver that sore feet! Every exercise is beneficial to you and it comes with ups and downs to your training routine, so get familiar with whats best for you. In fact, if you dont learn to do the exercises correctly you are prone to more training injuiries and that will ultimately hold you back in gaining muscles the most.

This video is just adding to the nonsense belief that only some awkward weird exercises can get you big while others wont by displaying this fit guy with a nice body. This guy already has a nice body, so all he needs to do it keep the shape so that his body has sufficient fitness to reduce risks of health issues with higher age, he does not need to gain more from a health point of view, at all.
The truth is, depending on what your shitty or good fitness currently looks like, for as long as your body is not used to an exercise in which it has not build sufficient muscles yet, it will definitely destroy enough muscle fibbres for you to gain muscle from it - even from these exercise, that are currently hard for you and that may look easy for others. So try to become fitter in whatever way fits your style and work on your imbalances!

Also: although i really like dragonball n stuff, those animes are an adaptation of the real world under relaxed assumptions, so NO YOU CAN NOT draw realistic benefits from anime back to the real world, it simply does not work this way.

textDisplay: Can you make ballet inspired workouts? Like for total balance, strength, flexibility & endurance? textDisplay:
Actually all you have to do is fast frequently.
Your body will resist structural adaptations if it doesn't think it can afford them.
You will then make more neural adaptations, and structural adaptations will be limited.
It's going to be incredibly limited though. Your strength blocks will become a lot smaller. Your tendons, and bones recover too slowly with less energy, and protien.
You would go until your body begins to stop you then just do a maintenance phase while you do emphisize skill work, then hit it again.
Even that is limited.
To be honest if you are far enough ahead on neural adaptations you don't have to be afraid of weighing more with structural adaptations.
You will keep your speed if you put strength first.

textDisplay:
Great video as always, Adam. To answer your question, yes farmers do dig holes, this is when you have to build or mend a fence. Usually, these are either small wooden logs or newer metal posts. Also, sometimes, we have to dig the truck or tractor out of a slippery, muddy field when trying to collect the square bales of hay, to restack in the barn. Then there's repairs, all of the time. Some of these include overhead work which you have to use a coordinated balance of stabilizer muscles and endurance with both types of fibers, since fatigue sets in and one set burns out into the next one. There is also birthing calves and taking care of the feeding with the heavy sacks of corn and/or grain. As for tractors, I know you accidentally misspoke and didn't mean pushing them, but there is having to jack one up and change that damn heavy tire! By the time you get the tire out of the flatbed and to the tractor, you're already pissed off and wanting to get it over with.

This is by no means an exhaustive list with examples, but the few that give a good general idea on what farmers do every day. to those who may not know, most farmers are professional. There is the small scale, where one raises and sells livestock, grows and sells fruit and vegetables, usually to local markets. Then there is the large scale, where most of us get all of our packaged food products because farmers are raising and selling animals for meat processing and packaging plants, fruits and vegetables for canning, or bottling with juices and baby foods, and so on. Funny thing is, if farmers suddenly stopped working, all grocery stores would be emptied and useless and we would have to revert to hunting and gathering again. Who, other than the Bioneers, would be able to physically and mentally do that - all while having to defend one's home from scavengers and always be on the alert for someone who would come and kill and take your spoils from a successful hunt?

textDisplay:
I think this is quite theoretical, from what I’ve seen over the years as a PT is that yes it is possible to get stronger without getting bigger but either it’s very early, when you first begin training (when you activate your muscle fibres/central nervous system, before the start of the process of hypertrophy) but it’s maxed out very quickly (about first 3 months), or it’s genetic; some people continue to get stronger over time without much hypertrophy occurring, just because they don’t have the right genetics for hypertrophy.

PS: for 99% of the time, the bigger your muscles are, the stronger you are. And even in the 1% of cases where it’s not, the person with the bigger muscles still has more potential to be stronger over someone who has less muscle fibres, they just might not be using their muscles as efficiently as someone who is stronger but with smaller muscles. Likewise if that same strong person without much muscle gained more muscle, they would always become stronger than before. Muscles create/generate force for movement. More and bigger muscles fibres= greater force generation potential. Muscle and strength go hand in hand.
